# Commit discipline

## One logical change per commit

- A refactor and a feature are two commits.
- A bug fix and an unrelated rename are two commits.
- Generated files / lockfiles / vendored deps go in their own commit.

## Conventional Commits, "why"-first

Format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <why-it-matters, imperative, <=72 chars>

<body explaining: what changed, why, alternatives considered, follow-ups deferred>
```

Allowed types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `docs`, `build`,
`ci`, `chore`, `revert`.

## Header rules

- Imperative mood: "add", not "added" / "adds".
- Lowercase after the colon.
- No trailing period.
- Aim for <=72 characters; hard limit 100.
- The subject after `:` should explain *why this commit matters*, not just
  what files changed.

## Body rules

For anything non-trivial (more than ~10 lines or any logic change):

- Blank line after the header.
- Wrap at ~72 chars.
- Cover: what changed, why, what was considered and rejected, any follow-ups
  deferred to a future commit.
- Reference the PR / issue / ticket if there is one.

## Good examples

```
feat(parser): detect Arabic poetic meter for line-break heuristic

The line-break engine in §2 needs to know the meter so it can avoid
breaking inside a foot. Considered hand-tuned regexes per meter but the
prosody table is small enough to encode directly. Deferred: caching the
meter per stanza — premature until profiling shows it matters.
```

```
fix(ui): prevent right-to-left bleed in mixed-text paragraphs

Paragraphs that mixed Arabic and Latin runs were inheriting the last
run's direction. Fix: explicit `dir` attribute per run. Considered the
CSS `unicode-bidi: isolate` route but it broke selection in Word's
rendering host.
```

```
refactor(io): extract file loading to prep for streaming

No behavior change. Splits `loader.py` into `read.py` + `parse.py` so an
upcoming streaming path can replace `read.py` without touching parsing.
```

## Bad examples (never do this)

- `update parser` — what changed? why?
- `fix bug` — which bug? why was it a bug?
- `WIP` — never commit WIP to a shared branch.
- `address review comments` — say *which* comments and *what* you changed.
- `refactor + add feature X` — two concerns, two commits.
